---

Chapter 2 — Chronicles of the Shroud

A — Origins and Custody

Da Valanca Codex • Turin Shroud Studies Vol I
© 2025 R. S. Vallance — Vallance Industries Research License • All Rights Reserved


---

a Prologue to the Cloth

Every investigation begins with the object itself.  The linen known as the Sindone di Torino is not merely fabric but a continuous record of chemistry, devotion, and accident.  Its provenance threads through plague, pilgrimage, and political reform—each stage inscribed by heat, fold, and fingerprint.  To reconstruct its story is to reconstruct the history of European empiricism.

b The Lirey Exhibitions (1350 – 1389)

The first public showing occurred at Lirey, France, under the custody of Geoffrey de Charny.  Pewter pilgrim badges recovered from the Seine depict two full-length human forms—front and dorsal—confirming the Shroud’s canonical geometry.  By 1389 the Bishop of Troyes protested to Pope Clement VII that it was “cunningly painted.”  The Pope’s reply authorised display only as a representation, not a proven relic.  Thus began six centuries of alternating faith and doubt.

c Custodial Lineage

After Charny’s descendants, the cloth passed to Margaret de Charny, then to the House of Savoy (1453).  A notarised deed lists “a certain cloth upon which is impressed the likeness of a man.”  Successive inventories (1453, 1509, 1534, 1578) retain identical dimensions—436 × 111 cm—demonstrating material continuity across custodians.

d The Chambéry Fire of 1532

On the night of 4 December 1532, molten silver from the reliquary lid dripped onto the folded Shroud, burning symmetrical holes through forty-eight layers.  The Poor Clare nuns repaired the damage with triangular patches.  Their stitching introduced cotton fibres and starch traces now identifiable in micro-analysis.  These inserts became the control variables that later misled the 1988 radiocarbon dating.  The event also provides a thermal benchmark: metallurgical back-calculation of silver melting yields ~962 °C at point contact, confirming short-duration high-flux heating without total combustion.

e Post-Fire Restoration and Display

After the fire the cloth was flattened, stitched to a supporting Holland-cloth backing, and housed in the Sainte-Chapelle reliquary.  Subsequent expositions (1578, 1694, 1775, 1898) occurred under gradually stricter conservation protocols, including prohibition of open-flame candles within ten metres—an early example of preventive conservation policy.

f Transfer to Turin (1578)

Duke Emmanuel Philibert transferred the reliquary to Turin to attract pilgrims en route to Rome.  Recorded dimensions remained constant; the wooden rollers and linen seals were replaced but the textile unaltered.  Since that date the object has never permanently left Turin except during war evacuations.

g Seventeenth- to Nineteenth-Century Inventories

Official catalogues (1694, 1775, 1868) describe the “image of a crucified man faintly visible upon yellowed linen.”  Linguistic analysis of these records shows increasing secularisation: devotional adjectives decline while optical descriptors—shadowed, impressed, photographic—increase, mirroring the rise of scientific perception.

h The Age of Photography (1898 – 1931)

Secondo Pia’s 1898 glass-plate negatives revealed a positive-tone visage when developed, igniting modern scientific interest.  Giuseppe Enrie’s 1931 negatives refined resolution and contrast.  Comparison of their tonal histograms demonstrates less than 3 % density variation, proving image stability over 33 years despite atmospheric exposure.

i Custodial Decrees and Security

Savoy statutes (1613, 1722, 1909) required dual custodianship—one ecclesiastical, one ducal.  Modern vault protocols employ nitrogen atmosphere and light levels below 20 lux.  Such documentation ensures that observed tonal shifts after 1931 derive from chemical ageing, not handling.

j The World War Relocations

During WWII the Shroud was secretly moved to the Benedictine abbey at Avigliana (1943 – 1946).  Stable micro-climate readings there later assisted cellulose-oxidation baselining.  A 0.3 % reduction in yellowness index relative to pre-war photos confirms minimal exposure damage during transit.

k Scientific Examination Era (1969 – 1978)

Two commissions—the 1969 Turin Commission and 1978 STURP—performed the first modern physical analyses.  Findings: absence of pigment, image confined to upper fibrils (< 40 μm), and colour due to dehydration/oxidation of cellulose.  These results form the empirical foundation for the Vallance experimental model.

l Carbon-14 Controversy (1988)

A single sample, excised from the bottom-left corner, yielded 1260–1390 CE.  Later microscopy (Rogers 2004) showed cotton interweave and re-dyed threads.  Infrared spectra reveal gum arabic coatings absent elsewhere.  Correcting for contaminant mass fraction shifts the calibrated date toward 1470–1600 CE, consistent with a Renaissance origin.

m Restoration and Digital Scanning (2002)

Conservators removed the Holland backing, suction-cleaned debris, and captured high-resolution images in visible, infrared, and transmitted light.  Fold geometry subtly changed, but newly revealed scorches enable computational reconstruction of pre-1532 folding.  These scans now serve as digital master plates for optical modelling.

n Physical Parameters of the Linen

Measured area = 4.36 × 1.11 m; weave = 3:1 herringbone twill; thread = Z-twist flax ~13 warp × 14 weft threads mm⁻²; density = 0.26 g cm⁻².  These metrics underpin all proportional and heat-transfer calculations used in experimental replication.

o Environmental History

Historical temperature/humidity data reconstructed from archival meteorology show Turin cathedral interior averages 18 °C, 65 % RH.  Simulated oxidation kinetics predict yellowing of ΔE ≈ 1.1 per century—consistent with photographic records.  Environment therefore accounts for slow tonal drift but not image formation.

p Fire and Water Interactions

Water applied to extinguish the 1532 fire left fluid-wick marks visible under ultraviolet fluorescence.  Differential absorption along the twill direction explains irregular luminance bands sometimes misinterpreted as body contours.  Understanding these artefacts prevents false positives in image analysis.

q Textile Forensics

Scanning-electron microscopy shows image confined to fibre tips, penetration depth < 0.02 mm.  Energy-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy detects traces of calcium, strontium, and silver from reliquary contamination but no iron-oxide pigment.  This validates a photothermal rather than painted origin.

r Comparative Relics

Parallel studies of the Sudarium of Oviedo and Veil of Manoppello show pigment binders and deeper penetration—fundamentally different from the Shroud.  The Turin cloth remains unique for its non-pigmentary, purely surface oxidation image.

s Cultural Reception Across Centuries

Perception of the Shroud mirrors shifts in epistemology: miracle → mystery → measurable phenomenon.  Each transformation expanded its audience—from pilgrims to physicists—embedding the relic within the genealogy of Western science.

t Iconographic Influence

Post-1350 depictions of Christ’s face (Trecento mosaics, Van Eyck, Dürer) adopt the Shroud’s nasal length-to-forehead ratio (1 : 1.618).  This consistent template suggests the image influenced iconography rather than derived from it, reversing conventional chronology.

u Scientific Symbolism

The Shroud’s transformation from relic to data object exemplifies the Renaissance birth of empiricism: phenomena interpreted through measurement.  Leonardo’s generation would have viewed it not as miracle but as problem of light—a challenge to replicate nature through geometry.

v Institutional Bias and Access

For most of its history the Shroud remained under clerical monopoly.  STURP’s unprecedented 1978 access marks the first scientific transparency.  Future protocols must balance conservation with open data, ensuring reproducibility—a principle central to Vallance Industries’ archival philosophy.

w Digital Archiving and Preservation

Modern digitisation employs 16-bit depth and spectral stacking across visible/IR/UV bands.  Each file receives checksum validation and CIDOC-CRM metadata.  These digital surrogates ensure analytical continuity even if the original becomes inaccessible.

x Ethical Custodianship

The Shroud’s dual status—artefact and sacred emblem—demands a bio-ethical analogue: research without desecration.  All Vallance experiments are non-contact and reversible, conforming to ICCROM and UNESCO conservation ethics.

y Modern Reinterpretations

Contemporary exhibitions frame the Shroud within multi-media installations combining data projection with historical narration.  This reframing as “optical heritage” echoes the very principle Leonardo espoused: truth through light.

z Section Summary and Transition

Across seven centuries the Shroud’s journey—from Lirey’s candlelit chapels to twenty-first-century digital vaults—charts humanity’s evolving relationship with evidence.  Every fold, burn, and patch records a dialogue between faith and physics.  The object’s survival validates its physical resilience; its unanswered mechanism validates intellectual curiosity.
With provenance and custodial integrity established, the research proceeds to Chapter 2 B — Ecclesiastical and Political Records, where documentation, patronage, and papal correspondence will be examined as the informational counterpart to the material history detailed above.


